</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>An <fr:em><fr:strong>inverse</fr:strong></fr:em> to a function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="erct-000X.xml"
addr="erct-000X"
title="Quasi-inverse">quasi-inverse</fr:link> equipped with an additional higher coherence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\chi  \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ  \eta  \sim  \epsilon \circ  f]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\circ  g \circ  f \sim  f]]></fr:tex> relating the (<fr:em>a priori</fr:em> incoherent) unit and the counit of the quasi-inverse. We will refer to a function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> equipped with an inverse as an <fr:em><fr:strong>invertible function</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
